{{Infobox ancient site |name = Bryn Gwyn stones |native_name = |alternate_name = |image = Bryn Gwyn slab stone with small adult 11102009.JPG |alt = Bryn Gwyn slab stone with small adult |caption = Bryn Gwyn slab stone |map = |map_caption = |map_type = Wales Anglesey |map_alt = Anglesey |coordinates = {{coord|53.177174|-4.302127|display=inline,title}} |map_size = |location = Brynsiencyn, Anglesey, Wales |region = Great Britain |type = [[Stone circle]] |part_of = |length = |width = |area = |height = 4m |builder = |material = stone |built = |abandoned = |dependency_of = |occupants = |event = |epochs = [[Neolithic British Isles|Neolithic]] |cultures = |excavations = 2010 |archaeologists = [[Gwynedd Archaeological Trust]] |public_access = Yes |condition = |website = |designation1 = Scheduled monument |designation1_number = AN022 |designation1_date = }} The '''Bryn Gwyn stones''' stand about {{convert|280|metres}} to the south-west of [[Castell Bryn Gwyn]], on the low ridge some {{cvt|2|metres|ft|0}} above the valley of the [[Afon Braint]] on the [[Isle of Anglesey]] in [[Wales]].<ref name="Cope1998">{{cite book |first=Julian |last= Cope |authorlink= Julian Cope |title= [[The Modern Antiquarian: A Pre-millennial Odyssey Through Megalithic Britain]] : Including a Gazetteer to Over 300 Prehistoric Sites |year=1998 |page=307 |publisher= Thorsons Pub |isbn= 978-0-7225-3599-8}}</ref> [[File:Bryn-gwyn Stones - geograph.org.uk - 978290.jpg|thumb|left|Bryn Gwyn stones in use as a gatepost]]
They are the tallest [[standing stone]]s in Wales, nearly {{cvt|4|metres|ft|disp=x| high (|)}}. In 1723 [[Henry Rowlands]] described them as part of a ruinous circle of eight stones, some {{cvt|16|metres}} across. An account of 1797 says that "ignorant country people supposing money was hid under them tore them up" and today only two stones, one slab and one pillar, stand in a modern field bank. Nothing else is visible on the ground, but a 2008 excavation found three pits of standing stones, two containing stone stumps,<ref>BRYN GWYN STONES, BRYNSIENCYN, ANGLESEY EVALUATION EXCAVATION 2008 PRELIMINARY REPORT. Project No. G1629. Report No. 790 Prepared for Cadw March 2009. By George Smith. "[http://www.walesher1974.org/her/groups/GAT/media/GAT_Reports/GATreport_790_compressed.pdf Report 790]". Accessed 31 Jan 2016.</ref><ref name="Cyfeillion Ymddiriedolaeth Archaeolegol Gwynedd 2009. pp 32-33">Cyfeillion Ymddiriedolaeth Archaeolegol Gwynedd, Haf 2009. Friends of the Gwynedd Archaeological Trust, Summer 2009. Prehistoric Funerary and Ritual Survey, pp 32-33.</ref> consistent with the record by Rowlands. Further excavations in 2010 identified the pits of three more removed standing stones, making seven identified in all of the eight expected to make up the original circle.<ref>BRYN GWYN STONES, BRYNSIENCYN, ANGLESEY: EXCAVATION 2010, PRELIMINARY REPORT. Project No. G1629. Report No. 942. Prepared for Cadw March 2011 By George Smith. Accessed 31 Jan 2016</ref><ref name=excavation>[http://www.heneb.co.uk/cadwprojs/cadwreview2010-11/funrit10-11.html A re-discovered stone circle, Bryn Gwyn, Anglesey] GAT preliminary excavation report and site plan, 2011.</ref>
The pit of a further stone, inside the circle, shows it was a 'blade-style' stone, with an alignment with the summer solstice sunrise and winter solstice sunset.<ref name=excavation/> A public footpath runs past the stones from Bryngwyn-mawr on the [[A4080 road]], continuing north-east on a low ridge past [[Castell Bryn Gwyn]] and some 800 metres further to [[Caer Lêb]]. From the Bryn Gwyn Stones the midsummer sun rises over the centre of Castell Bryn Gwyn.<ref>{{Watprn|GAT|3135}}, Archwilio archaeological database</ref>
In the 18th century a cottage was built with the wide stone as its end wall. Notches round its top show where roof timbers had been fitted. With the removal of the cottage (which had occupied an area inside the stone circle)<ref name=excavation/> the stones were used as a gateway through the field hedge.<ref>{{Watprn|coflein|302402}}, Coflein site database of [[RCAHMW]]</ref>
Further to the north-east at Tre'r Dryw Bach, another large [[stone circle]] was reported by 18th century visitors but has since been cleared away.<ref name="Cyfeillion Ymddiriedolaeth Archaeolegol Gwynedd 2009. pp 32-33" />
