{{refimprove|date=January 2015}}
In most [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] countries, a '''conveyancer''' is a specialist [[lawyer]] who specialises in the [[legal]] aspects of [[buying]] and [[selling]] [[real property]], or [[conveyancing]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.constitution.org/bouv/bouvier_c.htm | title=Bouvier's Law Dictionary | publisher=Constitution Society | date=1856 | accessdate=30 January 2015}}</ref> A conveyancer can also be (but need not be) a [[solicitor]], [[licensed conveyancer]], or a [[fellow]] of the [[Institute of Legal Executives]].
In the United Kingdom, conveyancers are regulated by an official body known as the Council for Licensed Conveyancers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conveyancer.org.uk/|title=CLC – The Specialist Property Law Regulator|website=www.conveyancer.org.uk}}</ref> Its main purpose is to set entry standards and regulate the profession of licensed conveyancers effectively in order to secure adequate consumer protection, promote effective competition in the legal services market and provide choice for consumers.
Services offered by conveyancers vary from Residential Conveyancing, [[Probate]] and [[Will (law)|Wills]]. Strong regulation is imposed to curb unfair practices which include among others false representation, exaction for hidden charges and double dealing.
In Kenya, a conveyancer can only be an admitted advocate holding a valid current practising certificate. The consequences of not holding such a certificate is fatal to any transaction he undertakes on behalf of his client, and will be void. The client is therefore under obligation to do his due diligence by ensuring that his conveyancer has a current valid practising certificate by confirming this with the law society of Kenya. This was authoritatively decided by the [[Court of Appeal of Kenya|Court of Appeal]] in its decision of National Bank of Kenya Ltd. v. Wilson Ndolo Ayah.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.kenyalaw.org/Downloads_FreeCases/70186.pdf | title=Civil Appeal 119 of 2002 | publisher=Kenya Law Reports | date=2009 | accessdate=30 January 2015}}</ref>
In Australia, a conveyancer is also known as a Settlement Agent.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.legalelements.com.au/conveyancing-brisbane/purchasing-a-house/how-do-conveyancers-operate-and-can-they-help/ | title=How Do Conveyancers Operate And Can They Help?| publisher=The Legal Elements | date=22 January 2014 | accessdate=30 January 2015 | author=Foyle, Brendon}}</ref>
In Canada, a conveyancer is a legal clerk or a paralegal who assist lawyers in all aspects of conveying real estate. == References == {{reflist}}
{{Law-stub}} {{Job-stub}}
[[Category:Law in the United Kingdom]] [[Category:Legal professions]] [[Category:Occupations]] [[Category:Solicitors]]

In [[comedy]], a '''dick joke''', '''penis joke''', '''balls joke''', '''cock joke''' or a '''knob joke''' is a joke that makes a direct or indirect reference to a human [[penis]] (known in slang parlance as a [[dick (slang)|dick]]), also used as an umbrella term for dirty jokes. The famous quote from [[Mae West]], "Is that a gun in your pocket or are you just excited to see me?" is cited as an example of a penis joke. The "dick joke" has been described as "often used as a metaphor for the male-defined nature of stand-up comedy".<ref name="Gilbert">Joanne R. Gilbert, ''Performing Marginality: Humor, Gender, and Cultural Critique'' (2004), p. 68.</ref> Dick jokes have also been noted to be both popular and effective with audiences:

{{quote|Comics use what "works," and dick jokes are guaranteed to amuse audiences of both genders in a surprising variety of contexts. Simply put, dick jokes get the quickest and biggest laughs, and in stand-up comedy, size does matter.<ref name="Gilbert"/>}}

==In comedy==
An important component of a dick joke is breaking a social taboo. As a Canadian comedian [[Ricky Blue]] puts it: "The trick is being able to speak the unspeakable and somehow get away with it."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tomifobia.com/ricky_blue/dick_joke.shtml|title=The world loves a good Dick joke|work=Log Cabin Chronicles|author=Ricky Blue|accessdate=2005-11-02}}</ref>

Comedian [[Bill Hicks]] satirized the popularity of dick jokes in his own act:

{{quote|He hasn't told any dick jokes. Doesn't he know he's in America? Doesn't he know about our puritanical self hatred of our own body and its desires, the only way we can find relief is through the medium of penis material?' Yeah, I'm totally aware of where I am, don't worry. The dick jokes are on their way.<ref>Bill Hicks, ''Love All the People'' (2009), "Appendix: Recorded Live in Denver, San Ramon, West Palm Beach and San Francisco (1990-93)".</ref>}}

However, due to their prurient nature, comedians who rely on explicit humor must find less controversial subject matter if they wish to expand their presence to more restrictive venues like [[network television]] and [[family film]]s. In short, "young professionals whose success has been achieved on the stepladder of dick jokes must eventually change their acts".<ref>Robert A. Stebbins, ''Laugh-Makers: Stand-Up Comedy as Art, Business, and Life-Style'' (1990), p. 103.</ref>

The impact of this kind of joke, as with most humor, may rest with the unspoken connotation.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} An example is the joke below set in a class in medical school:

{{quote|A professor gives his psychology class a spot quiz. One question he asks is, "What part of the human anatomy may expand up to ten times under certain circumstances?" He picks a rather overdressed girl in the front row to answer it. "Miss Callahan!" The indicated girl, who heard the question, stammers with some embarrassment: "Professor, I'd rather not answer that question." The professor says, "That's all right, Miss Callahan, you don't need to answer it. Is there anyone present who can answer it?" He notes an interested face in the back of the classroom. "Mr. Hawkins!" Hawkins says, "Yes, Professor, it is the pupil of the eye that may expand to ten times." The professor says, "That is correct, Mr. Hawkins." Then he turns to Miss Callahan. He says, "Young lady, two things are obvious from your reaction to this question. One, you haven't studied this week's assignment; and Two, I'm afraid marriage is going to be a tremendous disappointment to you."}}

Because the name [[Richard]] can be abbreviated as "Dick", in some jokes a person named "Richard" or "Dick" is presented as a [[double entendre]].<ref>Joel Stice, "[http://www.collegehumor.com/post/6986076/10-dicks-who-made-it-onto-the-local-news 10 Dicks Who Made it Onto the Local News]", ''[[CollegeHumor.com]]'' (August 15, 2014): "There's nothing wrong with the name "Dick" but when your name is literally a dick joke, maybe think about going by Richard".</ref>

