'''Renata Holod''' is an art/architectural historian and archaeologist of the Islamic world. She is the College for Women Class of 1963 Term Professor in the [[Humanities]] in the [[History of art|History of Art]] Department, and Curator of the [[Near East]] Section, [[University of Pennsylvania Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology|Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology]] at the [[University of Pennsylvania]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Renata  Holod {{!}} Penn History of Art|url=https://www.sas.upenn.edu/arthistory/people/renata-holod|website=www.sas.upenn.edu|publisher=University of Pennsylvania|accessdate=2 March 2017|language=en}}</ref> Holod has taught at Penn since 1972, and was a visiting Clark Professor at [[Williams College]] in 2002. She has conducted and/or directed archaeological fieldwork in [[Iraq]], [[Afghanistan]], [[Syria]], [[Iran]], [[Morocco]], [[Turkey]], [[Ukraine]], and [[Tunisia]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KCVzCwAAQBAJ&pg=PR11&lpg=PR11&dq=when+did+renata+holod+start+teaching+at+penn?&source=bl&ots=ikd3CQzW-G&sig=HVsTpKWAWd_o3ErgJYu5THu0O4U&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjG2ZzY1crTAhVGzmMKHQnbCHoQ6AEIODAD#v=onepage&q=when%20did%20renata%20holod%20start%20teaching%20at%20penn?&f=false|title=Envisioning Islamic Art and Architecture: Essays in Honor of Renata Holod|last=Roxburgh|first=David J.|date=2014-11-14|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9789004280281|language=en}}</ref>

Holod earned her B.A. degree in Islamic Studies at the [[University of Toronto]] in 1964; her M.A. in History of Art from the [[University of Michigan]] in 1965, and her Ph.D. in Fine Arts from [[Harvard University]] in 1972. As a professor, she has supervised over fifty Ph.D. theses from students in a range of fields, including History of Art, Architecture, Urban Planning, Religious Studies, Middle East Studies, and Art and Archaeology of the Mediterranean World.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kolbsociety.com/en/kolb-fellows-new/senior-fellows/81-renata-holod-ph-d|title=Holod, Renata, Ph.D.|last=Administrator|website=www.kolbsociety.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-04-30}}</ref>

In 1977, Holod was the Convenor of the [[Aga Khan Award for Architecture]] and Designer of the Award Procedures, served on the Steering Committee for the award in 1980-83 and 1993–96, and was Chair of the Master Jury in 1992.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KCVzCwAAQBAJ&pg=PR11&lpg=PR11&dq=when+did+renata+holod+start+teaching+at+penn?&source=bl&ots=ikd3CQzW-G&sig=HVsTpKWAWd_o3ErgJYu5THu0O4U&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjG2ZzY1crTAhVGzmMKHQnbCHoQ6AEIODAD#v=onepage&q=qasr&f=false|title=Envisioning Islamic Art and Architecture: Essays in Honor of Renata Holod|last=Roxburgh|first=David J.|date=2014-11-14|publisher=BRILL|isbn=9789004280281|language=en}}</ref> She has consulted on architectural projects in Iraq (the Abu Nuwas River Bank Project with Arthur Ericson Vancouver in 1981, and the Iraq State Mosque with [[Venturi, Rauch and Scott Brown|Venturi, Rauch, Scott-Brown]] in 1982-83);<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archnet.org/authorities/80/publications/10399|title=Rasem Badran {{!}} [eng] State mosque competition, Baghdad, Iraq {{!}} Archnet|website=archnet.org|access-date=2017-04-30}}</ref> the United States ([[The Islamic Cultural Center]] of New York, with [[Skidmore, Owings & Merrill|Skidmore, Owings and Merrill]] 1986-88);<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.som.com/projects/islamic_cultural_center_of_new_york|title=Islamic Cultural Center of New York|website=SOM|language=en-US|access-date=2017-04-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archnet.org/sites/2104/media_contents/22288|title=Islamic Cultural Center of New York {{!}}  {{!}} Archnet|website=archnet.org|access-date=2017-04-30}}</ref> and the [[United Arab Emirates]] (the Palm Jumeirah Gateway Bridge for [[The Palm, Dubai|The Palm Dubai]] with [[H2L2]] in 2003).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://structurae.net/structures/palm-jumeirah-gateway-bridge|title=Palm Jumeirah Gateway Bridge (Dubai, 2006) {{!}} Structurae|website=Structurae|language=en|access-date=2017-04-30}}</ref>

As a curator, Holod has created exhibitions in the [[United States]] (including “'From the Two Pens’: Line and Color in Islamic Art” at Williams College Museum of Art, October–December 2002,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XDLcBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA392&lpg=PA392&dq=%E2%80%9CFrom+the+Two+Pens%E2%80%9D++williams+college?&source=bl&ots=VYa9BsbG-7&sig=k3yId_b890zkj8h-vPR7--q2Dgw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi6scqu3MrTAhVO4mMKHVDpC7wQ6AEIPDAE#v=onepage&q=%E2%80%9CFrom%20the%20Two%20Pens%E2%80%9D%20%20williams%20college?&f=false|title=The Oxford Handbook of American Islam|last=Haddad|first=Yvonne Yazbeck|last2=Smith|first2=Jane I.|date=2014-01-01|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199862634|language=en}}</ref> “Archaeologists and Travelers in Ottoman Lands” at the [[Penn Museum]], September 2010-June 2011<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ottomanlands.com|title=home {{!}} Archaeologists & Travelers In Ottoman Lands|website=www.ottomanlands.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref>) and Turkey (“Osman Hamdi Bey and The Americans: Art, Diplomacy, Archaeology” at the [[Pera Museum]], Istanbul, October 2011-January 2012).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.peramuseum.org/Exhibition/Osman-Hamdi-Bey-and-the-Americans/89|title=Osman Hamdi Bey and the Americans|website=www.peramuseum.org|language=en|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref>

She serves on numerous advisory boards and committees, including the Advisory Board of [[Muqarnas (journal)|Muqarnas]]: Annual in Islamic Art and Visual Culture (since 1999);<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://agakhan.fas.harvard.edu/icb/icb.do?keyword=k69205&tabgroupid=icb.tabgroup104596|title=► Muqarnas § Aga Khan Program for Islamic Architecture|website=agakhan.fas.harvard.edu|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref>  the Scientific Committee of the Fondation [[Max van Berchem|Max Van Berchem]] (since 2001);<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.maxvanberchem.org/en/scientific-committee|title=Scientific Committee|last=Administrator|website=www.maxvanberchem.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref> the Advisory Board of the [[International Journal of Islamic Architecture]] (since 2012),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.intellectbooks.co.uk/journals/view-Journal,id=204/view,page=3/|title=Intellect Ltd.|website=www.intellectbooks.co.uk|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref> and the Advisory Board of [[Arts Asiatiques]] (since 2012).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.efeo.fr/base.php?code=98|title=EFEO - Publications - Arts Asiatiques|website=www.efeo.fr|language=en|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref> Holod is a Senior Fellow of the [[Kolb Society]] at the Penn Museum (elected 1989), and has been honored with the King Fahd Award for Teaching the Architecture of Muslim Cultures (1986), the Islamic Environmental Design Achievement Award (2004), and the Provost’s Award for Mentorship of Graduate Students (2010).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.kolbsociety.com/en/kolb-fellows-new/senior-fellows/81-renata-holod-ph-d|title=Holod, Renata, Ph.D.|last=Administrator|website=www.kolbsociety.com|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-04-30}}</ref> Her former students published a [[festschrift]] in her honor (“Envisioning Islamic Art and Architecture: Essays in Honor of Renata Holod”, edited by David J. Roxburgh) in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.brill.com/products/book/envisioning-islamic-art-architecture|title=Envisioning Islamic Art and Architecture {{!}} Brill|website=www.brill.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-30}}</ref>

Holod is a past President of the [[Historians of Islamic Art Association]] (2007–10). She has been member of the Board of Trustees of [[Ukrainian Museum|The Ukrainian Museum]] since 2011, and President since 2013.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ukrainianmuseum.org/trustees.html|title=Ukrainian Museum - Welcome, About, Trustees, volunteer, intern, opportunities|website=www.ukrainianmuseum.org|access-date=2017-04-29}}</ref>

==Works==
* ''Architecture and Community: Building in the Islamic World Today'' ([[Aperture]], 1983) {{ISBN|9780893811235}}
* (with [[Oleg Grabar]], James Knustad, and William Trousdale) ''City in the Desert'': ''Qasr al-Hayir East'' ([[Harvard University Press]], 1978). {{ISBN|9780674131958}}
* (with Ahmet Evin) ''Modern Turkish Architecture'' ([[University of Pennsylvania Press]], 1984) {{ISBN|9780812279252}}
* (with Hasan Uddin-Khan) ''The Mosque and the Modern World: Architects, Patrons and Designs Since the 1950s'' ([[Thames & Hudson|Thames and Hudson]], 1997) {{ISBN|9780500341551}}
* (with Salma Jayyusi, Attilio Petruccioli, and André Raymond) ''The City in the Islamic World'' ([[Brill Publishers|Brill]], 2008) {{ISBN|9789004162402}}

