{{refimprove|date=June 2010}} {{Infobox Italian comune | name = Rignano Flaminio | official_name = Comune di Rignano Flaminio | native_name = | image_skyline = Rignano_flaminio01.JPG | imagesize = | image_alt = | image_caption = The ancient Via Flaminia. | image_shield = | shield_alt = | image_map = | map_alt = | map_caption = | pushpin_label_position = | pushpin_map_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|42|12|N|12|29|E|type:city(7,714)_region:IT|display=inline}} | coordinates_footnotes = | region = [[Latium]] | metropolitan_city = [[Metropolitan City of Rome|Rome]] (RM) | frazioni = Capannacce, Case Morolo, Montelarco, Santo Sisini, Valle Spadana | mayor_party = | mayor = Fabio Di Lorenzi | area_footnotes = | area_total_km2 = 38.56 | population_footnotes = <ref name="istat">All demographics and other statistics: Italian statistical institute [[National Institute of Statistics (Italy)|Istat]].</ref> | population_total = 10237 | population_as_of = 30 November 2016 | pop_density_footnotes = | population_demonym = Rignanesi | elevation_footnotes = | elevation_m = 250 | twin1 = | twin1_country = | saint = | day = | postal_code = 00068 | area_code = 0761 | website = {{official website|http://www.comunerignanoflaminio.it}} | footnotes = }} '''Rignano Flaminio''' is a ''[[comune]]'' (municipality) in the [[Metropolitan City of Rome]] in the [[Italy|Italian]] region [[Latium]], about {{convert|35|km|mi}} north of [[Rome]]. It is across the [[Via Flaminia]].
Rignano Flaminio borders the municipalities of [[Calcata]], [[Capena]], [[Civitella San Paolo]], [[Faleria]], [[Magliano Romano]], [[Morlupo]], and [[Sant'Oreste]].
It has a station on the [[Ferrovia Roma-Viterbo|Roma-Viterbo]] railway.
==History== Agricultural settlements of the [[Capenati]] and [[Falisci]] in the area are attested from the 5th or 4th centuries BC. In the 6th century AD a popular pilgrimage church, entitled to St. Abondius and Abondantius, was created here; the saints' relics were moved to Rome, on the [[Tiber Island]], in 999. In 1159 [[Pope Adrian IV]] died at Rignano.
Rignano was first a possession of [[Santa Maria in Trastevere]] and then of the [[Savelli family]], who were shortly ousted by [[Pope Alexander VI]]. After the fall of the [[Borgia]], the Savelli regained it and held the fief until 1607, when they sold it to the [[Borghese]]. It later passed to the Muti, the Cesi and the Massimo families.
